  <div class="content">
    <h3>Overview</h3>

    <p>
      Woodland Resources              : The study of silviculture and silvics and their application to forest management to sustain the production of wood and other ecological goods and services such as wildlife, water and landscape in natural forests and rural environments (agroforestry). Acquisition of practical skills in forest surveying and computer simulation of forest growth.          </p>

    <p class="catalog-terms">
      Terms:              Winter 2015          </p>

    <p class="catalog-instructors">
      Instructors:                        Benoit Cote (Winter)                  </p>

    
          <ul class="catalog-notes">
              <li>Winter</li>
              <li>3 lectures and one 3-hour lab</li>
              <li>Prerequisite: ENVB 210 or ENVB 222 or ENVB 305 or permission of instructor.</li>
            </ul>
      </div>

  </div> <!-- /.node -->
              </div>
            </div>
          </li>
                </ul>
      
      
            </div>

    
  
  <div class="disclaimer">McGill School of Environment&mdash;2014-2015 (last updated Feb. 18, 2014) (<a href="/study/2014-2015/disclaimer">disclaimer</a>)</div>
  </div> <!-- /.node -->
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
          </div>
